body:
Can you attach an example that shows the issue?  (Must be openly licensed, ideally in test_regress format.)

```
`timescale 1ns / 1ps

interface generic_interface #(
                              parameter int ARB = 5
                             )
                             (
                              input clk,
                              input rst
                             );
    logic        valid;
    logic        ready;
    logic [31:0] data;

    modport slave(
                  input  valid,
                  output ready,
                  input  data
                 );

endinterface

class genericClass #(
                     int NUM_INTF = 5
                    );

    virtual generic_interface.slave #(5) vif;

endclass

module dut #(
             parameter int NUM_INTF = 5
            )
            (
             generic_interface.slave intf_s
            );

    genericClass #(NUM_INTF) genCls;

    initial begin
        genCls = new();
        genCls.vif = intf_s;
    end

endmodule

module tb_top();

    localparam int NUM_INTF = 6;

    generic_interface #(5) gen_if (tb_clk, tb_rst);

    dut #(NUM_INTF) u_dut(gen_if.slave);

    logic tb_clk, tb_rst;

    initial begin
        tb_clk = '0;
        tb_rst = '0;

        $finish();
    end

endmodule
```

```
The syntax error shows the following:

%Error: tb_top.sv:26:37: syntax error, unexpected '#', expecting IDENTIFIER or do or final or randomize
   26 |     virtual generic_interface.slave #(5) vif;
      |                                     ^
%Error: Exiting due to 1 error(s)
```

Please note that upon the removal of the parameter "#(5)" the code compiles without issue.

What 'verilator' command line do we use to run your example?

`verilator --top-module tb_top  --binary --assert -Wall -Wno-fatal --timescale 1ns/1ps --trace --trace-structs  ./tb_top.sv`

What 'verilator --version' are you using?  Did you try it with the git master version?

`Verilator 5.030 2024-10-27 rev v5.030-45-g2cb1a8de7`

Have not tried on master head.

What OS and distribution are you using?

Fedora

May we assist you in trying to fix this in Verilator yourself?

Yes.
